        <name>35.3.3.5 Exercise 1</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A box contains \({@aa@}\) bad tube(s) and \({@bb@}\) good tubes. Two are drawn out together. One of them is tested and found to be good. What is the probability that the other one is also good?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]&lt;/p&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;p&gt;A box contains \({@aa@}\) bad tube(s) and \({@bb@}\) good tubes, so, in total {@aa+bb@} tubes.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Let \(G_i=\{i^{th} \text{ tube is good}\}.\)&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;The probability to draw one good tube out of the box is \( G_1 = \displaystyle {@bb/(aa+bb)@}. \)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;If the first tube was good, then when the second tube is selected there are only {@bb-1@} good tubes left in the box which now contains {@aa+bb-1@} tubes.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Hence,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style="font-size: calc(0.90375rem + 0.045vw);"&gt;\(\text{P}(G_2|G_1)= \displaystyle {@ta1@}.\)&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</generalfeedback>
